# Method-Based Access Control Can Be Circumvented

## Vulnerability Type
Broken Access Control

## Difficulty
practitioner

## Platform
PortSwigger Web Security Academy

## Goal
Solve the lab by logging in with the credentials `wiener:peter` and exploiting flawed access controls to promote yourself to administrator.

## Root Cause
The application enforced access controls based on the HTTP request method. Certain administrative actions were restricted for one method but allowed using another HTTP method.

## Exploitation Steps
1. Browse the application
2. Log in using the provided user credentials
3. Observe the administrative functionality
4. Intercept the request using Burp Suite
5. Modify the HTTP method used in the request
6. Forward the modified request
7. Successfully promote the user account to administrator

## Impact
An attacker can bypass access control restrictions and gain unauthorized administrative privileges.

## Prevention
- Enforce authorization checks independently of HTTP methods
- Validate user permissions on every request
- Restrict sensitive actions server-side
- Implement proper role-based access control

## What I Learned
This lab helped me understand how inconsistent authorization checks across different HTTP methods can lead to privilege escalation vulnerabilities.
